He felt naked without his beret. He must have misplaced it somewhere but couldn't remember.

"This just ain't my day." - Bill

He darted across the dancefloor, shoving past mesmerized guests, desperate to find an exit. There was none.

"Oh, this is gonna get bad..." - Bill

This new coat was adorned with his old medals. He needed to escape this party, and he knew it.

"Agh! Hell with this!" - Bill
A mask he found himself wearing at the masquerade ball.
She moved through the crowd, bumping into guests randomly to gauge their reactions.
She peered through the narrow holes of her gold mask, watching the guests. She had to find the perfect candidate.
She seized her victim from behind and drove the knife into his throat. Leaving him with no escape, the jagged blade tearing mercilessly into his flesh.
A mask he found himself wearing at the masquerade ball. Through the spectacle of his own torment, he has always been hiding from the truth.

A mask she found herself wearing at the masquerade ball.
A sharp whistle pierced the air and dazzling colors lit up the sky over the bay. He watched as the families, friends, and lovers cheered all around him.
A mask he found himself wearing at the masquerade ball.
As he made his way through the crowd, he heard some of his students calling for him. They begged him to join them for the grand finale, and he happily agreed.
Parents carried their children on their shoulders, just like his uncle used to carry him. His chest began to ache, and he decided to head home.
A mask they found themself wearing at the masquerade ball.
Crimson blossoms would sprout through her skin as nature reclaimed her dead body.
Soon she would be one with these flowers; the thought was both terrifying and comforting.
Petals would spread around the ring in a deadly wreath. She closed her eyes and waited.
It was hard to see through the darkness, but the knight appeared to be more monster than man, powered by some sinister darkness.
They came across a towering knight on their way to the cave. In the dark of the night, his eyes seemed to glow red like fire.
Their screams were suddenly silenced. Only the thuds of their severed bodies hitting the ground echoed in the mountain pass.
A mask she found herself wearing at the masquerade ball.
The voice kept calling her, like a kid asking to play hide-and-seek. She grabbed a bottle of champagne, ready to strike, and turned to face... It.
She heard someone calling her name. A voice she recognized, but something was off, and she couldn’t tell what.
She stared at the twisted figure as its skin oozed, materializing blue fabric. The champagne crashed to the floor. Escape was never an option.
When it was her turn, she rolled to attack Joey's fighter. She rolled a critical hit this time, leaving Frank and Julie stunned.
Joey wouldn't stop gloating about Susie's failure. While the group planned their escape from the castle, Susie decided to put Joey in his place.
Joey's saving throw failed. Susie's rogue plunged the knife into his fighter and kicked him in the shin for good measure.
He chose a class that could express pain through fury, like he did through music. He just had to think through his next course of action.
The Barbarian crashed through the door, shattering it with a single strike. It was a moment his new friends talked about even after the game was over.
His character stepped on a trap, and a solid stone door came down behind him. He needed a way out to help his friends in battle.

While they were exploring a magical forest, the DM warned the party about an approaching monster. They couldn’t risk the fight.
The roll was successful. She distracted the monster and helped her friends. Meg sat back in her chair and let out a deep sigh of relief.
As a Ranger, she felt responsible for their safety. She rolled the d20 and held her breath until the die came to a stop.
A mask she found herself wearing at the masquerade ball.
With a playful glimmer, she shared a story about a woman who lived by the sea. Every night, she watched as the stars became one with the vast ocean.
When she awoke, she could feel her heart overflowing with untamed magic that could bring both wonder and terror.
But from the calm water emerged a dark figure with skin that reflected the light of the moon. Her strength faded as she fainted, clutching her heart.
The story felt strangely familiar. The navigator's journals told of string of islands brimming with supernatural energy.
The journal would not help him find his students, but it was further proof that he wasn't the only one tormented by the supernatural.
Pages were torn from the journal, and the final entries were incomprehensible. Yoichi pored over his maps but couldn't find the mysterious islands.
A mask she found herself wearing at the masquerade ball.
A mask he found himself wearing at the masquerade ball.
They all had their converter glasses on to see the planet’s true colors. The environments here were a far cry from what he remembered back on Earth.
They each found a shimmering rock to take as a souvenir. Together, they watched as the binary suns rose over the purple ocean.
They lay in the hot pink sand and spent the night talking about their dreams and aspirations. Gabe wanted to find a new home for his parents on some faraway planet.
He tried to fit in at the party, but realized they were all muttering nonsense to each other. Like a mad crowd.
He felt watched, like helpless prey out in the open. He tried to leave, but the door he came in through disappeared.
He panted and shook his jacket to catch his breath. All the masks stared at him, making the room feel smaller.
She lowered her sunglasses and saw her parents swimming and laughing in the water, not ready to leave yet. Over their heads, dark clouds appeared out of nowhere.
As her parents stumbled out of the water, Sable couldn’t help but laugh. Her wish had been granted beyond expectations.
She felt the first drops on her shoulders before torrential rain poured down. The other beachgoers panicked, scrambling to grab their things.
